00:00:53,121 --> 00:00:55,454
      the distinctive sound     
       of the tin whistle       

11
00:00:55,456 --> 00:00:58,257
      is characteristic of      
    the traditional music of    

12
00:00:58,259 --> 00:01:01,193
 england, ireland, and scotland.

13
00:01:01,195 --> 00:01:03,529
         when this flute        
     was first manufactured     

14
00:01:03,531 --> 00:01:05,131
    in the mid-19th century,    

15
00:01:05,133 --> 00:01:08,067
    it sold for just a penny,   
      making it affordable      

16
00:01:08,069 --> 00:01:10,770
    and earning its nickname    
      "the penny whistle."      

17
00:01:13,541 --> 00:01:18,076
 this u.k. company was the first
  factory to make tin whistles. 

18
00:01:18,078 --> 00:01:22,614
  in 1843, the company produced 
   whistles using tinplate --   

19
00:01:22,616 --> 00:01:26,752
   that's tin-coated steel --   
  from british metal foundries. 

20
00:01:31,092 --> 00:01:34,760
   a press strikes each sheet   
      with a dye 20 times,      

21
00:01:34,762 --> 00:01:40,299
   stamping out 20 flat shapes  
         called blanks.         

22
00:01:40,301 --> 00:01:43,502
     each blank contains six    
 finger holes toward the bottom 

23
00:01:43,504 --> 00:01:48,641
    and a rectangular opening   
  called a fipple near the top. 

24
00:01:48,643 --> 00:01:51,110
      a technician inserts      
       one blank at a time      

25
00:01:51,112 --> 00:01:55,114
   into a custom-made mandrel,  
      then turns the crank.     

26
00:01:55,116 --> 00:02:00,652
the mandrel rolls the flat blank
          into a tube.          

27
00:02:00,654 --> 00:02:03,122
     while some tin whistles    
          are straight,         

28
00:02:03,124 --> 00:02:05,591
   this company's tin whistles  
          are tapered.          

29
00:02:05,593 --> 00:02:11,096
       the signature shape      
  creates a distinctive sound.  

30
00:02:11,098 --> 00:02:15,000
    next, a technician slides   
  four tubes into tapered slots 

31
00:02:15,002 --> 00:02:16,935
     on a custom-built jig.     

32
00:02:16,937 --> 00:02:20,272
   the slots align the tube's   
     edges, creating a seam     

33
00:02:20,274 --> 00:02:24,944
that will prevent air blown into
the instrument from leaking out.

34
00:02:24,946 --> 00:02:28,014
       the seam is coated       
   in a chemical called flux.   

35
00:02:28,016 --> 00:02:32,951
     without it, solder wire    
  won't adhere to the tinplate. 

36
00:02:32,953 --> 00:02:35,421
     using a custom-designed    
         soldering gun,         

37
00:02:35,423 --> 00:02:39,291
 the technician melts lead-free 
   solder wire onto the edges,  

38
00:02:39,293 --> 00:02:41,560
      fusing them together.     

39
00:02:41,562 --> 00:02:43,495
                     ♪          

40
00:02:43,497 --> 00:02:46,365
       the flux and solder      
        are both nontoxic       

41
00:02:46,367 --> 00:02:48,500
    since they're being used    
        on an instrument        

42
00:02:48,502 --> 00:02:52,304
    that goes into the mouth.   

43
00:02:52,306 --> 00:02:56,041
a worker washes the tin whistles
     in mild soap and water     

44
00:02:56,043 --> 00:02:58,510
   to remove any excess flux.   

45
00:02:58,512 --> 00:03:00,179
                     ♪          

46
00:03:00,181 --> 00:03:02,915
     another technician uses    
       a custom-made file       

47
00:03:02,917 --> 00:03:07,652
 to scrape off any excess solder
 and ensure the seam is smooth. 

48
00:03:07,654 --> 00:03:10,389
   then he shapes the top end   
       of the tin whistle       

49
00:03:10,391 --> 00:03:13,325
      with this custom-made     
         squaring tool.         

50
00:03:13,327 --> 00:03:16,328
 the round top of the instrument
         is now square.         

51
00:03:16,330 --> 00:03:19,331
                     ♪          

52
00:03:19,333 --> 00:03:22,534
    the tin whistles are sent   
  to the factory's paint shop.  

53
00:03:22,536 --> 00:03:25,471
 an operator hooks the whistles 
          onto a track          

54
00:03:25,473 --> 00:03:28,140
       that moves through       
        a paint chamber.        

55
00:03:28,142 --> 00:03:31,343
 inside, automated nozzles spray
         the instruments        

56
00:03:31,345 --> 00:03:35,214
       with powder paint.       

57
00:03:35,216 --> 00:03:37,349
      then the tin whistles     
        head to an oven,        

58
00:03:37,351 --> 00:03:39,752
      which bakes the paint     
         for 20 minutes,        

59
00:03:39,754 --> 00:03:44,290
        at a temperature        
   of 255 degrees fahrenheit.   

60
00:03:44,292 --> 00:03:46,826
    as each instrument exits    
            the oven,           

61
00:03:46,828 --> 00:03:49,261
      the operator inspects     
         the paint job.         

62
00:03:53,167 --> 00:03:55,167
 a pad printer spreads gold ink 

63
00:03:55,169 --> 00:03:58,637
 into the engraved company logo 
           and design.          

64
00:03:58,639 --> 00:04:00,573
    the pad picks up the ink,   

65
00:04:00,575 --> 00:04:06,378
 and stamps the logo and design 
       on the instrument.       

66
00:04:06,380 --> 00:04:09,782
to create the narrow air channel
      that produces sound,      

67
00:04:09,784 --> 00:04:11,584
    a wooden plug is created    

68
00:04:11,586 --> 00:04:14,920
and placed above the mouthpiece,
           or fipple.           

69
00:04:14,922 --> 00:04:18,057
   the plug is made from cedar  
          or beechwood.         

70
00:04:18,059 --> 00:04:20,792
        this type of wood       
     contains closed grains     

71
00:04:20,794 --> 00:04:24,730
     that prevent swelling.     

72
00:04:24,732 --> 00:04:28,067
      after pieces of wood      
 are cut to the required shape, 

73
00:04:28,069 --> 00:04:30,869
       a tin whistle tuner      
     applies a water-based,     

74
00:04:30,871 --> 00:04:36,275
    nontoxic adhesive inside    
   the top of the instrument.   

75
00:04:36,277 --> 00:04:38,811
      then he takes a plug,     

76
00:04:38,813 --> 00:04:43,215
       sands the cut edge,      

77
00:04:43,217 --> 00:04:45,351
   and glues it into the top.   

78
00:04:45,353 --> 00:04:52,224
                     ♪          

79
00:04:52,226 --> 00:04:54,292
  once he's completed sanding,  

80
00:04:54,294 --> 00:04:57,095
     the whistle specialist     
      tunes the tin whistle     

81
00:04:57,097 --> 00:04:59,365
   by inserting a sizing tool   
           in the gap           

82
00:04:59,367 --> 00:05:01,901
      between the tinplate      
          and the plug.         

83
00:05:01,903 --> 00:05:06,037
 he gently hammers the tinplate 
   against the plug and tool.   

84
00:05:06,039 --> 00:05:09,375
    this step adjusts the air   
 channel to the required width, 

85
00:05:09,377 --> 00:05:11,910
perfectly tuning the instrument.

86
00:05:11,912 --> 00:05:14,780
          after tuning          
     50 or so tin whistles,     

87
00:05:14,782 --> 00:05:17,049
      he performs a musical     
           spot-check.          

88
00:05:17,051 --> 00:05:19,585
                     ♪          

89
00:05:19,587 --> 00:05:22,454
   once the adhesive has cured  
          for 24 hours,         

90
00:05:22,456 --> 00:05:25,324
    the tin whistle is ready    
         for packaging.         

91
00:05:25,326 --> 00:05:27,593
      after the instrument      
        has been cleaned,       

92
00:05:27,595 --> 00:05:29,794
      a technician includes     
        a fingering chart       

93
00:05:29,796 --> 00:05:31,864
      and a sheet of tunes      
         in the package         

94
00:05:31,866 --> 00:05:35,400
      so that beginners can     
  teach themselves how to play. 

95
00:05:35,402 --> 00:05:37,202
                     ♪          

96
00:05:37,204 --> 00:05:40,673
      the tin whistle comes     
     in the key of c and d.     

97
00:05:40,675 --> 00:05:44,943
 the musical landscapes of jigs,
     reels, highland flings,    

98
00:05:44,945 --> 00:05:48,180
 and other traditional melodies 
      of the british isles.     

